    "what_description": "Bacopa monnieri is an annual or perennial herbaceous plant belonging to the family Plantaginaceae, native to tropical, subtropical, and temperate regions of the world. It has simple, petiolate, and alternate leaves, measuring 3-10 cm in length, with an ovate or elliptical shape and a cordate base. The leaves are dark green in color, with a glabrous or slightly hairy surface, and contain a single midrib with prominent secondary veins. The plant produces small, white, or pale blue flowers in axillary cymes, measuring 4-6 mm in diameter, and bears two-celled capsules that split open at maturity to release numerous seeds. Bacopa monnieri is commonly known as Brahmi in Ayurvedic medicine, where it has been used for centuries to enhance cognitive function and memory.",
